t-display}\n```{=html}\n<div id=\"body-section\">\n<br/>\n<div id=\"big-section-title\">Criminal Offense</div>\n<br/>\n<div id=\"regular-text\">Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit, sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt ut labore et dolore magna aliqua. Ut enim ad minim veniam, quis nostrud exercitation ullamco laboris nisi ut aliquip ex ea commodo consequat. Duis aute irure dolor in reprehenderit in voluptate velit esse cillum dolore eu fugiat nulla pariatur.</div>\n<br/>\n<div id=\"visualization\">No Data</div>\n<div id=\"visualization\">No Data</div>\n<br/>\n</div>\n```\n:::\n:::\n\n\n</center>\n<br>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n## Parole Eligibility\n\n<center>\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n```{=html}\n<div id=\"body-section\">\n<br/>\n<div id=\"big-section-title\">How is Parole Eligibility Determined?</div>\n<br/>\n<div id=\"regular-text\">Most offenders are sentenced to a determined, maximum term of years. These inmates become eligible for parole when they have served one-third of that maximum sentence. However, all offenders must serve a minimum of 60 days before becoming eligible for parole. The court has the discretion to sentence offenders to a minimum term not to exceed one-half of the maximum sentence where it is 'clearly convinced that the aggravating factors substantially outweigh the mitigating factors' in the case. Third and fourth time offenders must serve one-half, and two-thirds, respectively, of their maximum term. The court is also required to set a minimum term between one-third and one-half of the maximum sentence for crimes involving use of a firearm, causing bodily injury while eluding arrest, and repeat convictions for drug possession with intent to sell. Some crimes have mandatory minimum terms that are not discretionary. For example, public officers or employees of the state who commit a crime that 'involves or touches' their official duties have mandatory minimum terms based upon the degree of the crime and proximity to their official duty. New Jersey's parole release statute mandates that a prisoner 'shall be released on parole at the time of parole eligibility,' unless there is a showing by a preponderance of the evidence that the inmate has failed to participate in his or her own rehabilitation, or will violate the conditions of release. The sentencing judge must inform the offender of his or her minimum parole eligibility date as well as what credits can be earned to reduce the duration of the sentence. The Parole Board has discretion to decrease an inmate's parole eligibility period for 'exceptional progress, as evidenced by documented participation and progress in institutional or community educational, training or other programs,' but not below a court-ordered minimum sentence. The Board and the Department of Corrections may also make a parole contract with an offender which reduces the inmate's primary parole eligibility date in exchange for completion of specific programs. If convicted of crimes resulting in consecutive sentences, the terms are added to arrive at an aggregate term equal to the sum of the terms.</div>\n<br/>\n<br/>\n</div>\n```\n:::\n\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n```{=html}\n<div id=\"body-section\">\n<br/>\n<div id=\"big-section-title\">Parole-Eligible Prison Population</div>\n<br/>\n<div id=\"regular-text\">In 2020, there were NA people were eligible for parole but still in prison for new crimes, with original sentence lengths ranging from 1 to 25 years. This group made up NA% of the prison population.</div>\n<br/>\n<div id=\"bar-chart\">\n<div id=\"htmlwidget-bfa94b76555a17a7b8d2\" style=\"width:100%;height:250px;\" class=\"highchart html-widget \"></div>\n<script type=\"application/json\" data-for=\"htmlwidget-bfa94b76555a17a7b8d2\">{\"x\":{\"hc_opts\":{\"chart\":{\"reflow\":true,\"width\":700,\"height\":270},\"title\":{\"text\":\"Prison Population by Parole Eligibility Status in 2020\"},\"yAxis\":{\"title\":{\"text\":\"\"},\"type\":\"linear\",